  "stage": {
    "id": "core_architecture",
    "stageNumber": 2,
    "title": "Core Transformer Architecture",
    "roomWidth": 20,
    "roomHeight": 15,
    "concepts": [
      {
        "id": "transformer_architecture",
        "title": "The Transformer Architecture",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Encoder-decoder structure with stacked layers\n- Self-attention replaces recurrence for sequence modeling\n- Constant number of operations between any two positions\n\nIn their landmark 2017 paper, Vaswani et al. asked a radical question: what if we built a sequence model using only attention? The result was the Transformer—an architecture that 'dispenses with recurrence and convolutions entirely.'\n\nThe Transformer maintains the encoder-decoder structure from seq2seq but replaces RNN layers with self-attention layers. The encoder is a stack of 6 identical layers, each containing self-attention and a feed-forward network. The decoder is similar but adds cross-attention to look at encoder outputs.\n\nThe magic is in the connectivity: in an RNN, position 1 must pass through positions 2, 3, ..., n-1 to reach position n. In a Transformer, every position directly connects to every other position in a single operation. This enables massive parallelization and makes learning long-range dependencies trivial.",
        "position": {
          "x": 5,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "scaled_dot_product_attention",
        "title": "Scaled Dot-Product Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Dot product measures query-key similarity\n- Scaling factor prevents gradient vanishing in softmax\n- More efficient than additive attention for large d_k\n\nThe Transformer's attention mechanism has an elegant formula:\n\n```\nAttention(Q, K, V) = softmax(QK^T / √d_k) V\n```\n\nWhy the √d_k scaling? Vaswani et al. discovered that for large dimensions, dot products grow large in magnitude. When you pass large values into softmax, it saturates—most weights become nearly 0 or 1, and gradients vanish.\n\nImagine you're voting on 100 options. Without scaling, the most popular choice might get 99.99% of votes, making it impossible to learn from the others. The √d_k factor keeps votes more balanced, allowing the model to learn nuanced attention patterns.\n\nThis scaled dot-product attention is both simpler and more efficient than the additive attention from Bahdanau et al., which required a learned weight matrix.",
        "position": {
          "x": 9,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "multi_head_attention",
        "title": "Multi-Head Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- h=8 parallel attention heads with d_k=d_v=64\n- Each head learns different attention patterns\n- Outputs concatenated and projected back to model dimension\n\nRather than performing a single attention operation, the Transformer uses multi-head attention: h=8 parallel attention operations, each with its own learned projections.\n\nWhy multiple heads? Think of reading a sentence for different purposes. One 'head' might focus on grammatical relationships (subject-verb), another on semantic meaning, another on positional patterns. Single-head attention can only capture one view; multi-head attention captures many simultaneously.\n\nThe implementation splits the 512-dimensional model into 8 heads of 64 dimensions each. Each head performs scaled dot-product attention independently, then outputs are concatenated and projected back to 512 dimensions. The ablation studies showed that both too few heads (1) and too many (32) hurt performance—8 was the sweet spot.",
        "position": {
          "x": 13,
          "y": 4
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "self_attention",
        "title": "Self-Attention",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- Q, K, V derived from the same input sequence\n- Captures dependencies regardless of distance\n- O(1) sequential operations vs O(n) for RNNs\n\nSelf-attention is the special case where queries, keys, and values all come from the same sequence. Each position creates a query ('what am I looking for?'), a key ('what do I have to offer?'), and a value ('here's my content').\n\nEvery position then attends to every other position—including itself. In the sentence 'The cat sat on the mat,' when processing 'sat,' self-attention can directly look at 'cat' (the subject) and 'mat' (nearby context) with equal ease, regardless of distance.\n\nThe computational implications are profound: RNNs need O(n) sequential operations for information to flow from position 1 to position n. Self-attention does it in O(1)—a single matrix multiplication connects all positions simultaneously. This is why Transformers train so much faster on parallel hardware.",
        "position": {
          "x": 7,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      },
      {
        "id": "positional_encoding",
        "title": "Positional Encoding",
        "content": "Key ideas:\n- sin/cos functions at different frequencies encode position\n- Allows model to extrapolate to longer sequences\n- PE(pos, 2i) = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\n\nHere's a subtle problem: attention treats the input as a set, not a sequence. Without positional information, 'dog bites man' and 'man bites dog' would look identical to the model!\n\nVaswani et al. solved this by adding positional encodings to the input embeddings. They chose sinusoidal functions:\n\n```\nPE(pos, 2i) = sin(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\nPE(pos, 2i+1) = cos(pos / 10000^(2i/d_model))\n```\n\nThink of it like a clock: the second hand moves fast (high frequency), the minute hand slower, the hour hand slowest. Each position gets a unique combination of 'times' across multiple clocks, creating a fingerprint.\n\nWhy not learned embeddings? Sinusoidal encodings let the model extrapolate to sequences longer than any seen during training. The ablations showed learned embeddings work about equally well, but sinusoidals generalize better.",
        "position": {
          "x": 11,
          "y": 10
        },
        "type": "text"
      }
    ],
    "quiz": {
      "id": "quiz-stage-2",
      "question": "Why does the Transformer need positional encodings?",
      "type": "multiple-choice",
      "options": [
        "To reduce memory usage",
        "Because attention is position-agnostic—without them, word order is lost",
        "To speed up training"
      ],
      "correctAnswer": "Because attention is position-agnostic—without them, word order is lost",
